### Setup Fidelity and Regularization Matrices

1. Set up an xGrid and then map it to the new xMapped space. The fitting will be done in the mapped space. 
2. y is converted to log10 space because log10(y) is smoother than y.
3. Call regularizeNdMatrices. Get the fidelity matrix, Cfidelity, and the regularization matrix, Lregularization (in other cases, Lregularization is "matrices" if there is more than one input).
4. Combine the fidelity matrix, Cfidelity, and the regularization matrix, Lregularization, into one composite matrix, C.
5. Create the corresponding vector to C, d.

::: {#811833cf .cell execution_count=5}
``` {.matlab .cell-code}
xGrid = {linspace(min(x),max(x),1000)};
xGridMapped = {mapping(xGrid{:})};
yLog10 = log10(y);
smoothness = 5e-4;

[Cfidelity, Lregularization] = regularizeNdMatrices(xMapped, xGridMapped, smoothness);
C = vertcat(Cfidelity,Lregularization{:}); % note this line of code works even if Lregularization has more than one cell

dFidelity = yLog10;
dRegularization = zeros(size(C,1)-size(Cfidelity,1),1);
d = vertcat(dFidelity, dRegularization);
```
:::


### Setup the Constraint Matrix

In this case, the desired constraint is that the lookup table is monotonically increasing. Also,
the bound is that no value in the final table is less than `1e-2` in original `y` units. Since we
solve for `yLog10Grid`, the lower bound is imposed in log space as `yLog10Grid >= log10(1e-2)`.


The constraints are formed as inequalities like this:

 $$ A*y_{\log 10,Grid} \le b $$ 

::: {#c979c8c7 .cell execution_count=6}
``` {.matlab .cell-code}
    % Monotonic constraint matrix
    [Amonotonic,bMonotonic] = monotonicConstraint(xGrid);

    nGridPoints = length(xGrid{1});
    yMin = 1e-2;

    % Bound constraint matrix
    Abound = sparse(nGridPoints,nGridPoints);
    Abound = spdiags(-ones(nGridPoints,1),0,Abound);

    % bound constraint vector
    bBound = -log10(yMin) * ones(size(Abound,1),1);

    % Composite constraint matrix and vector
    A = vertcat(Amonotonic, Abound);
    b = vertcat(bMonotonic, bBound);
```
:::


### Solve for the lookup table Using lsqConstrainedAlternative

Using the provided solver `lsqConstrainedAlternative` to find the lookup table `yGrid1`.


Create a function for use in evaluation.

::: {#9d62c6f7 .cell execution_count=7}
``` {.matlab .cell-code}
    tic;
    yLog10Grid1 = lsqConstrainedAlternative(C,d,A,b);
    toc;
    yLog10GridFunction1 = griddedInterpolant(xGridMapped, yLog10Grid1,'linear');
    yFunction1 = @(x) 10.^yLog10GridFunction1(mapping(x));
```

